We have always known that our leaders only look polished whenever they are signing for sitting allowances in their air-conditioned chambers, but whenever they go down to the grassroots to connect with their people their mouths have always spewed filth only fit for the Dandora dumpsite.
We had hoped that the battery of media cameras in Msambweni would have caused our political class to ask their tailors to stitch their mouths and only leave a small hole for passing food, but we have since discovered that whoever bewitched our politicians died with the antidote.





But worse is the behaviour of the citizens around politicians who defile public order. There were people cheering on when those demeaning statements were being made. The faces were happy, and there was no indication they were bribed to be happy, as they clapped their hands like penguins, laughed hysterically at those distasteful jokes.
It shows we are the ones responsible for abetting these bad manners from our politicians. Kenyans are always in love with drama at first sight. Had drama been a person there wouldn’t have been one Kenyan still single and searching.
We love our politics drunk and disorderly. A politician coming to take us through their manifesto has a higher chance of being booed off stage, but the one with dramatic details of how their opponents have been sneaking into a witchdoctor’s lair at ungodly hours carrying a human skull and drinking crocodile urine will have the DJ punctuate his speech with a shattering jingle to work the crowd into a frenzy just to make it good.



